<body>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" align="center" style="text-align:center"><b style="mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal"><span style="font-size:14.0pt;font-family:Arial">The six trig functions
and identities<o:p>
</o:p>
</span></b><span style="font-family:Arial"><o:p>
</o:p>
</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="tab-stops:76.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial">The
following diagrams are taken from the IES java applet in Japan at <a href="http://www.ies.co.jp/math/java/trig/sixtrigfn/sixtrigfn.html">http://www.ies.co.jp/math/java/trig/sixtrigfn/sixtrigfn.html</a>
, a very important way of looking at all 6 trig functions at once. The color
coding is the same as in the applet. Don uses these diagrams to get his students
to show the relationships (make identities-equations that are true for all
substitutions) between the 6 trig functions, expressing the </span><b style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="font-family:Arial;color:red">tan</span></b><span style="font-family:Arial">gent,
</span><b style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="font-family:Arial;color:fuchsia">cot</span></b><span style="font-family:
Arial">angent, </span><b style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="font-family:Arial;color:blue">sec</span></b><span style="font-family:
Arial">ant and </span><b style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="font-family:Arial;color:#993300">c</span></b><span style="font-family:
Arial">o</span><b style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="font-family:
Arial;color:#993300">s</span></b><span style="font-family:Arial">e</span><b style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="font-family:Arial;color:#993300">c</span></b><span style="font-family:Arial">ant
in terms of the</span><b style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="mso-bidi-font-size:
12.0pt;font-family:Arial;color:yellow;mso-text-raise:-2.0pt">
 </span></b><img border="0" src="../images/6trigf1.jpg" width="26" height="19" align="middle"><span style="font-family:Arial">e
and/or </span><span style="mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Arial">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial">
</span><b style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="font-family:Arial;color:lime">cos</span></b><span style="font-family:
Arial">ine, the basis of all the trigonometric identities. <o:p>
</o:p>
</span><span style="font-family:Arial"><o:p>
</o:p>
</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="tab-stops:76.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial">This
will be done by using the three similar right triangles in Figure 1. The
triangles are similar because their corresponding angles are equal (the</span><img border="0" src="../images/6trigf2.jpg" width="26" height="19" align="middle"><span style="font-family:Arial">
 [right] angles, the ' [dot] angles, and the</span><img border="0" src="../images/6trigf3.JPG" width="26" height="19" align="middle"><span style="font-family:Arial">
 (alpha) angles). In similar triangles, the corresponding sides are proportional.
We will call the three triangles <span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal; font-family: Arial"><b><font size="4">s</font></b></span><b style="mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal"> </b>(for <b style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal">s</b>mall), <span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal; font-family: Arial"><font size="4"><b>m</b></font></span>
 (for <b style="mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal">m</b>edium) and <b style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal">L</b> (for <b style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal">L</b>arge).
There are three things we have to keep track of in writing the proportions'
one is which pair of <b style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal">triangles</b> we are
using, two, which pair of <b style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal">sides</b> we
are using, which are opposite the corresponding pair of <b style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal">angles</b>.<o:p>
</o:p>
</span><span style="font-family:Arial"><o:p>
</o:p>
</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" align="center" style="text-align:center"><img border="0" src="../images/6trigf4.jpg" width="625" height="228"></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family:Arial">We'll start by finding
the </span><b style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="font-family:Arial;color:red">tang</span></b><span style="font-family:Arial">ent
of </span><img border="0" src="../images/6trigf3.JPG" width="26" height="19" align="middle">, <span style="font-family:Arial">and
go from the</span>  <b> m</b><span style="font-family:Arial">edium</span> <span style="font-family:Arial">triangle
to the <b style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal">s</b>mall triangle in <b> Figure 2</b>:<o:p>
</o:p>
<span style="mso-text-raise:-16.0pt"> </span>
<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp;</span><o:p>
</o:p>
</span></p>
